{
    "path": "/string-conversion",
    "title": "Converting to a string (str)",
    "syntax": {
        "code": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span><span>(</span><span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">20</span><span>)</span>",
        "description": "We call the function <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span> with the number <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">20</span> as an argument. This tells the computer to convert the number into a string. Strings are required when you want to join text and numbers together, like in a message."
    },
    "content": [
        {
            "header": "What are we doing?",
            "content": "We are converting a number into a string using the <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str()</span> function. This allows us to treat the number like text."
        },
        {
            "header": "Why do we need this?",
            "content": "You cannot combine (concatenate) a number directly with a string. If you try <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">\"hello\" + 5</span>, Python will give you an error. Using <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str()</span> turns the number into text so it can be combined with other strings."
        },
        {
            "header": "How do we use it?",
            "content": "You wrap the number or value you want to convert with <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str()</span>. For example: <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">42</span>) will return the string <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"42\"</span>."
        },
        {
            "header": "What does it return?",
            "content": "It returns a string version of the number. You can now use it inside other strings, such as: <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">print</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"The answer is \"</span> + <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">42</span>))."
        }
    ],
    "note": {
        "content": [
            {
                "header": "Only works for display",
                "content": "If you convert a number to a string, you can't do math with it anymore. <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"5\" + \"3\"</span> will give you <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"53\"</span>, not 8."
            },
            {
                "header": "Going the other way",
                "content": "If you have a string that contains digits, like <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"10\"</span>, you can turn it back into a number using <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">int()</span>."
            }
        ]
    },
    "examples": {
        "header": "Examples",
        "content": [
            {
                "description": "Example 1: Converting a number to a string",
                "code": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">100</span>)",
                "result": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"100\"</span>"
            },
            {
                "description": "Example 2: Concatenating a string and a number",
                "code": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">25</span>) + <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\" is the number\"</span>",
                "result": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"25 is the number\"</span>"
            },
            {
                "description": "Example 3: Using str() in print statements",
                "code": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">print</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"The answer is \"</span> + <span style=\"color:var(--syntax-func)\">str</span>(<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-num)\">42</span>))",
                "result": "<span style=\"color:var(--syntax-string)\">\"The answer is 42\"</span>"
            }
        ]
    }
}
